data.content:
## What happened

This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change. In .NET 10, the compiler's new built-in span conversions cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`.

`ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a ref struct and **cannot be represented in expression trees**, so the compiled/interpreted expression throws at runtime.

## Fix

Cast to `IEnumerable<int>` or use `.AsEnumerable()` to force binding back to `Enumerable.Contains`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three force the compiler to pick the `IEnumerable<T>` overload, which is expression-tree safe. The same pattern applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays (now binds to the in-place `Span` version returning `void`).
